Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince or grate @garlic{2%clove}. Trim @scallions{2}; cut whites into 1-inch pieces
and thinly slice greens.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pot{} over medium-high heat. Add garlic; cook,
stirring constantly, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Add 3 1⁄2 cups water (7 cups for 4 servings), @pork ramen stock concentrate{2%unit},
and @chicken stock concentrate{1%unit}. Cover and bring to a boil, then reduce heat to low.

  > You'll add more to the pot in Step 5.

Meanwhile, heat a medium #dry pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce};
cook, turning occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy, ~{6-10%minutes}.

  > If your pan seems dry, add a drizzle of oil.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Wipe out pan. Once bacon
is cool enough to handle, roughly chop.

Heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for bacon over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites
and @spinach{5%ounce}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until scallions are browned and
spinach is wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

  > For 4 servings, you may need to cook spinach in batches.

Meanwhile, add @ramen noodles{4.5%ounce} to pot with broth. Simmer, stirring occasionally,
until noodles are tender, ~{2%minutes}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} if desired.

Divide ramen between large #soup bowls{}.

Top with bacon, spinach, and scallion greens. Sprinkle with as many @chili flakes{1%teaspoon}
as you like and a few @crispy fried onions{1%unit}.

  > Don't add all the crispy onions to the ramen just yet! Add them as you eat to keep them crispy.

  > Bacon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.